{% extends 'base.html.twig' %}

{# #############################################
#                 VARIABLES                   #
############################################# #}

{% set title = 'Figurations' %}

{# #############################################
#               TITLE BLOCK                   #
############################################# #}

{% block title %}
    {{ title }}
{% endblock %}


{# #############################################
#             PAGE HEADER BLOCK               #
############################################# #}

{% block pageheader %}
    <ol class="breadcrumb">
        <li><a href="{{ path('homepage') }}">Home</a></li>
        <li class="active">{{ title }}</li>
    </ol>
    <h1>{{ title }}</h1>
<div class="fig-desc">
    <p>
        The two main research questions driving this project were: 
    </p>
    <ol>
        <li><em>How</em> is Photoshop(ping) inscribed in these videos?</li>
        <li><em>What</em> figurations are generated and/or sustained through these inscriptions?</li>
    </ol>
    <p>We use figurations to refer to any type of techno-social typification. For example, Donna Haraway (1997: 11) uses ‘figures’ to refer to the “necessarily tropic quality of all material-semiotic processes”. A key element of any figuration involves a shared purpose or relevance-frame (Couldry &amp; Hepp 2016: p.66). By setting out to identify Photoshop figurations we believe that we are taking an important step towards gaining a better understanding of the creative technicities that underpin much of contemporary digital culture. </p>
    
    
    
    <p>To answer the first of the above two questions, we created individual profiles for each of the videos collected for the research. (see <a>Project Documentation</a> for details of collection process) The answers to the second question were generated by synthesizing the data collected for each of the video profiles into <em>figurations</em>. Click on each of the figuration names to find a short description of each one. Each figuration was based on the types of “purpose” identified for each of the individual video profiles.</p> 
    <details open="open">
        <summary>References</summary>
        <ul class="bibliography">
            <li>Couldry, N., &amp; Hepp, A. (2016). <em>The mediated construction of reality: Society, culture, mediatization</em>. Cambridge, UK : Polity Press.</li>
            <li>Haraway, D. J. (1997). <em>Modest_Witness@Second_Millennium.FemaleMan_Meets_OncoMouse: Feminism and technoscience</em>. New York: Routledge.</li>
            <li>Ito, M. (Ed.). (2010). <em>Hanging out, messing around, and geeking out: Kids living and learning with new media</em>. Cambridge, Mass.: MIT Press.</li>
        </ul>
    </details>
</div>
{% endblock %}

{# #############################################
#                BODY BLOCK                   #
############################################# #}

{% block body %}
   
    

    {% for term in figurations %}
        {% set path = path('figuration_show', {'id': term.id}) %}
        {% include('panel.html.twig') with {title: term.label, videos: term.videos, useFiguration: 'false', path: path} %}
    {% endfor %}
{% endblock %}
